{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"Across regions, consistency remains strong overall. 

Nationally, ANC1 vs. ANC4 consistency is very high (100%), with all regions meeting the benchmark. However, Penta1 vs. Penta3 consistency is weaker, averaging 94% and dropping as low as 75% in Mudug (Galmudug) and Hiiraan regions, underscoring where data plausibility checks are most critical.

"},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"94f96848-5e34-425b-a09e-79ec325393ed","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Internal consistency"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Deliveries by skilled birth attendants closely tracked expectations through mid-2025, reflecting steady service utilization.

Deliveries by caesarian section showed a period of surplus in 2023, followed by a brief disruption in late 2024, when reported service use fell ~10% below expected levels, before returning to expected trends through mid-2025. 

Shortfalls and surpluses in caesarean deliveries could reflect reporting completeness issues rather than true service changes."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"a19b1433-440f-4123-a63a-c2bab8d4d86c","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Delivery by skilled birth attendant remained stable, while caesarean section trends showed potential reporting-driven fluctuations"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, the mean DQA score remained stable, decreasing slightly from 95% in 2022 to 93% in 2025. National mean scores are high, showing that on average, Somalia's HMIS data is close to the desired quality standard.

Across districts, all scores remained above 80% in 2025.

Although many facility-months don’t meet all criteria, they are close on average — suggesting that small improvements in reporting practices could bring most facilities above the threshold."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"da716f6b-abd4-4a55-b149-56a4454b29da","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"PNC1 for newborns showed persistent disruptions in 2023-25, averaging ~24% lower than expected, with ~16,700 visits in June 2025 (~20% lower).

Postnatal care for mothers also fell below expectations from the end of 2023 to mid-2025, averaging ~9% lower, with ~26,100 visits in June 2025 (~8% lower).

Across both indicators, the shaded shortfalls reflect a mix of service use and reporting disruptions, and the pattern appears to be driven largely by reporting completeness issues rather than true declines in postnatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"413db1fe-09e8-4b5e-b3d6-6316dc783df0","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Postnatal care shortfalls likely reporting-driven, with larger gaps for newborns"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, the overall DQA score declined slightly from 75% in 2022 to 71% in 2025.

Several regions achieved strong results above 85% in 2025, including Karkaar, Mudug (Puntland), Nugaal, Sanaag, Sool, Bakool, and Bay. 

However, data quality has declined in many areas, with Benadir, Hiiraan, Middle Shebelle, Lower Juba, Ayn and Ras-Asayr falling below 65%. These regions show the greatest need for renewed support to strengthen reporting completeness as of 2025."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"3d0f3ecc-b1e8-4cd3-b2dd-55b0823e65ae","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 showed disruptions in mid-2025, averaging ~63,900 visits per month vs. ~70,400 expected (~9% lower), with ~62,900 visits in June 2025 (~11% lower than expected). 

ANC4 largely tracked expected trends throughout the period, without notable disruptions.

Far fewer women progress from ANC1 to ANC4, underscoring a persistent continuity gap in antenatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"f13bc674-ef5d-4619-9723-9bf804e56ee5","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC service shows disruption in 2025; ANC4 stays near trend, but continuity gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","titleTextRelFontSize":10,"subTitleText":"","subTitleTextRelFontSize":6,"presenterText":"","presenterTextRelFontSize":4,"dateText":"","dateTextRelFontSize":3,"logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","sectionTextRelFontSize":8,"smallerSectionText":"","smallerSectionTextRelFontSize":5},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"span":3,"markdown":"Postnatal care for newborns fluctuated through 2023 and 2024 before rising in early 2025, reaching nearly 21,000 visits by mid-year.

Postnatal care for mothers remained consistently higher over the period, with modest variation and a notable increase in 2025 to ~29,000 visits, showing similar growth in 2025 relative to newborn follow-up.

Addressing the gap between newborn and maternal postnatal visits remains important to ensure both are reached consistently and continuity of care is maintained across the postnatal period."},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"dd7772cf-8e1e-4eda-926a-3a5bd9dd5b20","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in postnatal care"}}

