{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","titleTextRelFontSize":10,"subTitleText":"","subTitleTextRelFontSize":6,"presenterText":"","presenterTextRelFontSize":4,"dateText":"","dateTextRelFontSize":3,"logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","sectionTextRelFontSize":8,"smallerSectionText":"","smallerSectionTextRelFontSize":5},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false,"span":3,"markdown":"Outpatient utilization remained broadly stable from 2023 to 2025, with periodic short-term fluctuations. 

Service volumes reached ~8.5 million in mid-2023, followed by a sharp but temporary decline in early 2024. Utilization rebounded quickly and remained relatively stable through late 2024 and 2025, with minor mid-year dips and recoveries, reaching a high of ~8.6 million in May 2025.

Overall, the trend indicates steady outpatient service provision and use."},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"99a978df-b836-40ad-b1e8-2d166a26eaa0","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":"opd","replicateBy":"indicator_common_id"},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in outpatient visits"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"Deliveries by skilled birth attendant closely tracked expectations through mid-2025, reflecting steady service utilization.

Deliveries by caesarian section showed a period of surplus in 2023, followed by a brief disruption in late 2024, when reported service use fell ~10% below expected levels, before returning to expected trends through mid-2025. 

Shortfalls and surpluses in caesarean deliveries could reflect reporting completeness issues rather than true service changes."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"faec8702-26c8-4c73-a28c-698b2aacfb6e","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Delivery by skilled birth attendant remained stable, while caesarean section trends showed potential reporting-driven fluctuations"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"image","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgFile":"4134210786_8bb9eb2bb6_o.jpg","imgFit":"cover","markdown":"","imgStretch":true,"imgHeight":250},{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"primary","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"markdown":"The FASTR approach uses routine HMIS data to monitor how service delivery shifts over time.

By comparing observed vs. expected service volumes — adjusted for seasonality and historical trends — we can identify disruptions or surpluses in key health services.

This analysis provides a timely, system-wide perspective, highlighting where and when service use deviates from expected patterns. Findings generate actionable evidence to guide rapid responses, helping sustain continuity of essential care during funding uncertainty or operational change."}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Tracking Utilization of Essential Services Using HMIS Data","useFooter":false,"footerLogos":[]}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"*TO UPDATE: ANC1 showed disruptions in mid-2025, averaging ~63,900 visits per month vs. ~70,400 expected (~9% lower), with ~62,900 visits in June 2025 (~11% lower than expected). 

ANC4 largely tracked expected trends throughout the period, without notable disruptions.

Far fewer women progress from ANC1 to ANC4, underscoring a persistent continuity gap in antenatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"578b5973-f85e-4ce8-b1e3-db8a1de810e6","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC service shows disruption in 2025; ANC4 stays near trend, but continuity gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"*TO UPDATE: PNC1 for newborns showed persistent disruptions in 2023-25, averaging ~24% lower than expected, with ~16,700 visits in June 2025 (~20% lower).

Postnatal care for mothers also fell below expectations from the end of 2023 to mid-2025, averaging ~9% lower, with visits ~26,100 visits in June 2025 (~8% lower).

Across both indicators, the shaded shortfalls reflect a mix of service use and reporting disruptions, and the pattern appears to be driven largely by reporting completeness issues rather than true declines in postnatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"e679251c-7706-4d29-adbf-98296848b8e4","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Postnatal care shortfalls likely reporting-driven, with larger gaps for newborns"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 trends were more volatile, with several surpluses in 2023 followed by disruptions throughout 2024 and early 2025, averaging ~13% below expected levels during the disruption periods. In 2025, volumes alternated between peaks of surplus and valleys of disruption, converging by September 2025 when actual and expected volumes aligned.

ANC4 volumes closely tracked expected trends through 2023, before consistent disruptions across 2024 and 2025, averaging ~11% below expected levels in both years.

Far fewer women progress from ANC1 to ANC4, underscoring a persistent continuity gap in antenatal care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"578b5973-f85e-4ce8-b1e3-db8a1de810e6","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC service shows disruption in 2024 and 2025, with more volatility in disruptions and surpluses in ANC1"}}

